  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Develops global standards and recommendations\n- Monitors countries' anti-money laundering efforts\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides recommendations for preventing money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets international banking standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establishes regulatory frameworks for EU member states\n\nThese laws typically require:\n- Financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Customer identification and verification\n- Record-keeping\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Cooperation between international law enforcement agencies\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and the Proceeds of Crime Act in the United Kingdom.\n\nThe goal is to make it harder for criminals to disguise illegally obtained money as legitimate income.",
